The sheet bend, also known as the becket bend, weaver's knot, and weaver's hitch, is a bend knot used to join two ropes together. It is effective in binding lines of different diameter or rigidity securely together, although it tends to work loose when not under load.

The bowline is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a rope. It is easy to tie and untie, and it is often referred to as the "King of the knots" due to its importance. The bowline is one of the four basic maritime knots, along with the figure-eight knot, reef knot, and clove hitch.

The two half-hitches is a binding knot or hitch knot consisting of an overhand knot tied around a post, followed by a half-hitch. It is a simple and effective knot for securing a rope to a post or other object.

Wotherspoon's art explores the concept of illusions, which are distortions of the senses that reveal how the brain organizes and interprets sensory stimulation.

Illusions can be categorized into three main types: literal optical illusions, physiological illusions, and cognitive illusions. Literal optical illusions create images that differ from the objects that make them, while physiological illusions result from excessive stimulation of specific sensory mechanisms. Cognitive illusions, on the other hand, arise from unconscious inferences. Pathological visual illusions occur due to exaggerated physiological visual perception mechanisms.

Wotherspoon's artwork also draws inspiration from the concept of vanitas, a category of symbolic works of art that emphasize the transient nature of earthly life and the worthlessness of material pursuits. The Latin phrase "Vanitas vanitatum omnia vanitas," meaning "All is vanity, all is vanity, all is vanity," is a prominent theme in vanitas art. This phrase originates from the Ecclesiastes, a book in the Old Testament that reflects on the futility of human endeavors.

In his famous drawing "All Is Vanity," C. Allan Gilbert employs a double image to create a visual pun. The image of a woman admiring herself in a mirror, when viewed from a distance, appears to be a human skull. This artwork serves as a memento mori, a reminder of the inevitability of death and the transient nature of life.

In summary, George A. Wotherspoon's optical illusion art prints explore the concept of illusions and draw inspiration from the vanitas theme. His artwork challenges the viewer's perception and reminds them of the fleeting nature of earthly life.
